article.headline: Butler scores six points late to spark Heat
article.linkText: Rookie Butler helps Heat hold off Cavaliers
article.story:
MIAMI (AP) -- A pair of rookies, Caron Butler and Dajuan Wagner, stepped up in the crucial moments Saturday night. The victor in their first encounter was Butler. Butler scored six of his team-high 16 points in the final two minutes as the Miami Heat held on to hand the Cleveland Cavaliers their 14th consecutive loss, 85-79. "The challenge is to win basketball games night in and night out,'' Butler said. "He's a great player and we will see each other for many years to come in this league.'' After the Cavaliers cut a 10-point deficit to 79-74 on two free throws by Milt Palacio and a 3-pointer by Wagner, Butler secured Miami's victory with a baseline jumper with 1:08 remaining and a slam dunk off a missed 3-pointer by LaPhonso Ellis with 45 seconds left. Wagner led the Cavaliers, who were without the suspended Ricky Davis, with 28 points. Davis was suspended for two games by coach John Lucas for an on-court argument with teammate Tyrone Hill on Friday night. Despite his point total, Wagner lamented over a missed 3-pointer in the final seconds. "It don't mean nothing if you don't win,'' Wagner said. "But we are getting better. We just have to go out there and keep playing.'' Playing another solid game for the Heat was center Brian Grant. The 6-foot-9 Grant, usually outmatched in height against most of the league's centers, finished with 14 points and 10 rebounds and was especially effective with four jump shots in the third quarter. Grant now has seven double-double performances this season. "This is probably the best shooting game I've had from the outside all year,'' Grant said. "My feet were planted I was looking at the rim and I felt that the ball was going to go in every time.'' After a close first half in which neither team led by more than six points, Grant scored eight points in the first six minutes of the third period to help the Heat build a 54-46 lead. Ellis had two short jumpers and 3-pointer from the baseline as the Heat maintained their eight-point lead to finish the quarter. "Everyone on our team made a nice contribution to the victory,'' Ellis said. "Down the stretch when we needed to, we made the shots.'' Game notes
The Cavaliers attempted 39 free throws to the Heat's 10. ... Heat C Vladimir Stepania missed Saturday's game because of back spasms. ... The Heat had a season-high 14 steals, including four by Grant ... Cavaliers rookie forward Carlos Boozer had his third consecutive double double since joining the starting lineup, finishing with 15 points and 11 rebounds. ... During his 13-year NBA career, Cavaliers guard Bimbo Coles has shared the backcourt with dozens of players. Now he can boast of playing alongside a father and son. Coles played with Milt Wagner when he was a rookie with the Miami Heat in 1990-91, and now is a teammate of Wagner's son, Dajuan, with the Cavaliers.
